er happen. Its instructions must specify the exact response format unambiguously, with the verdict grammar and the closed rejection-reason set generated into the prompt, plus a parse-and-retry and a shape test, so an out-of-format reply is impossible in practice. *admission control*] High High Zero [])) (4oev ([(Technology (Software (Distributed ProtocolDesign)))] Principle [There should be no NOTA between components. Daemons and components exchange binary protocol data; the CLI is the translation/debugging surface that can wrap a normal call in a debugging request with options such as where logs should be displayed or stored. *IPC*] High High Zero [])) (5hjv ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Constraint [All Spirit Signal, Nexus, and SEMA operations must be declared in the schema files first; generated schema types are the source of every operation data type, and handwritten Rust may only implement behavior on those generated nouns.] High High Zero [])) (61lk ([(Technology (Software (Data Modeling))) (Technology (Software (Programming Compilation)))] Clarification [All text-based program code is pseudocode: the compiler must infer meaning by parsing text, which opens a large correctness gap. Sema exists to close that gap and is to become the fully correct data system in which code and data are typed structure rather than text. NOTA and the schema language are the deliberate half-step from text toward full correctness: positional, strict, fully typed. The Rust runtime is the current center because it is the superior runtime available today.] High High Zero [])) (7xnx ([(Technology (Software (Distributed ProtocolDesign)))] Decision [The guardian is a strict admission-control gate for every working-signal submission. Approval is a high bar, not the default. The guardian judges the whole submitted operation across all relevant dimensions read from its justification: whether the testimony is real and supports the statement, whether the justification warrants the operation, whether the domain and privacy are right, whether certainty and importance clear their burdens of proof, whether the submission is durable intent rather than task state, whether it duplicates or contradicts active intent, whether it is affirmatively framed, and whether the submitted operation is the correct intent-maintenance operation. For a proposed fresh Record, the guardian must strictly ask whether the same psyche statement should instead edit an existing record through Clarify, Supersede, ChangeRecord, ResolveClarification, Retire, or Remove. If the submission refines, narrows, corrects, or explains an identifiable prior record, the guardian rejects the fresh Record and remands the submitting agent to the edit operation. A justification may reference existing records and propose a cross-record operation, for example replacing several existing records with one or more new records at stated importances; the guardian judges that whole proposed operation as part of its single yes or no. *admission control*] High High Zero [])) (88eq ([(Technology (Software (Operations ReleaseEngineering)))] Decision [|Component upgrade protocol via Nix-flake versions — universal to every persona component that needs to upgrade. Each component's Nix flake captures the running-production version (the last known-working main of that component, pinned in the flake) as one input, the local in-development version (whatever the developer machine is running) as another, and additional named variants like unstable and testing as further inputs. All upgrade sequences are expressed in the Nix-flake-version structure. Tests run through Nix (which means commit-first — uncommitted local state is invisible to the Nix evaluator). The flake-input-as-deployed-version pattern is the workspace's upgrade substrate.|] High High Zero [])) (88mw ([(Technology (Software (Distributed ProtocolDesign)))] Decision [The guardian needs proper per-operation prompts: each operation type gets de