e the real cutover: the daemon live-generation-set, GC-roots, and event-log state persisted on sema-engine with self-resume on restart, rather than running a first cutover on in-memory state. The psyche judges the durable DB small and straightforward, not a big deal. Resolves the in-memory-versus-durable-first question in favour of durable-first.] High Minimum Zero [])) (oj3i ([(Technology (Software Data))] Decision [|Zero certainty IS the removal-candidate state in Spirit: zero certainty means the record has no value, so it must not surface by default. The default Observe query excludes Zero-certainty records. Query gains a certainty selection with a floor whose default is Minimum (excludes Zero); querying by an explicit certainty floor is generally supported, and seeing Zero-certainty records requires an explicit certainty selection (e.g. floor Zero / Any). This unifies removal-candidate with zero certainty rather than an arbitrary ad-hoc query. *query processing*|] High Minimum Zero [])) (olj1 ([(Technology (Software (Programming CodeGeneration)))] Principle [|Lowered schema output uses fully-qualified universal identifiers — namespace path prefixed to each name so collisions are impossible across components. The fully-qualified form is self-documenting; the sugar (transient) form gives expressive authoring power. Both forms equivalent; lowered is for verification + machine consumption + correctness checking by reading; sugar is for human authoring. The lowering process makes the schema a giant self-documented artifact.|] High Minimum Zero [])) (olwm ([(Technology (Software (Data Modeling)))] Principle [Schema and assembled-schema notation must truthfully represent the underlying data type shape. A homogeneous container must not be used for heterogeneous fields, and semantically empty wrapper records must not be introduced just to make an encoding fit; the representation should use the real product, sum, map, scalar, or typed common element that the data actually