ogy (Software (Programming CodeGeneration)))] Principle [The assembled schema tree is the complete input to Rust generation, including code to read and write NOTA text and portable rkyv binary data for SEMA and signal formats; Rust emission may later be invoked from a single macro that reads repository schema files.] High Minimum Zero [])) (07pn ([(Technology (Software Distributed))] Decision [Every message carries an ORIGIN ROUTE as automatic metadata that is NOT declared in the schema - it is implicit on every message - acting as a return address that travels the whole way through signal then nexus then sema and back, so a reply is associated with the originating query when it returns. The origin route is internal to each component, a short statistically-unique identifier with effectively no clashes; it need not be a long hash, it is just a return address echoed back. Refines the message-identity intent records 930 960 by making the correlation identity an implicit round-trip return-address metadata field rather than a schema-declared field. *remote procedure call*] Medium VeryHigh Zero [])) (izib ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Design)))] Decision [Domain subdomains are mandatory all the way to a leaf, so a domain value is always complete. DomainScope is not Domain with optional payloads; it is a separate generated prefix language over the same recursive domain tree, a ScopeOf construct, where stopping early is the prefix semantics rather than optional subdomain data. Every scope segment is a typed enum variant and the notation stays clean with no Some or None exposed; the generator owns the internal representation] Medium VeryHigh Zero [])) (mn3k ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Decision [Domain relations live as first-class highly visible schema-declared vocabulary in a dedicated taxonomy schema surface, a new schema interface kind alongside the plane schemas, not an ad-hoc data file. The relation and expansion mechanism is meant to be reusable across components such as the mind] Medium VeryHigh Zero [])) (o8x5 ([(Technology (Software (Distributed EventDrivenArchitecture)))] Decision [|NEXUS is the mail keeper - the in-between runtime layer that owns mail tracking and Signal-to-SEMA translation; when Nexus has the mail, the mail is in the BEING-PROCESSED state; Nexus IS the runtime representation that a mail is being processed; basic Nexus actions are: submitting query to Nexus (execution action) and getting a reply (state change or SEMA reply) which the Nexus then translates back into the Signal reply for the Signal plane; the daemon has THREE EXECUTION CENTERS - Signal (communication messaging), Nexus (execution + mail keeper + translator), SEMA (state); the complete flow is Signal IN -> Nexus accepts mail (mail enters being-processed) -> Nexus translates to SEMA query -> SEMA engine runs and produces state change + SEMA reply -> Nexus receives SEMA reply (mail has reached state and gotten response) -> Nexus translates SEMA reply to Signal response with logging that the response has been seriously received because there has been a response -> Signal OUT; this consolidates records 935 (Communicate + signal-frame + mail + database marker) + 963 (mail-mechanism + on_sent hook) + 964 (three schema types) + 965 (Nexus as execution+IO+UI) - the on_sent hook fires when Signal hands mail TO Nexus; the database marker travels on the SEMA reply that Nexus receives and propagates in the Signal response; UI and external-IO uses of Nexus from 965 are SPECIFIC USES of the more fundamental in-between translator + mail keeper role|] Medium VeryHigh Zero [])) (xqkv ([(Technology (Software (Observability Tracing)))] Decision [The schema-derived runtime should support an optional testing/instrumentation build surface where generated objects and engine interface usage can emit structured trace events to a logging socket. The trace exists to prove actual use of Signal, Nexus, and SEMA interfaces during tests, not merely that their symbols exist in source files.] Medium VeryHigh Zero [])) (3got ([(Technology (Software Distributed))] Decision [Communicate is its own TRAIT - the wire interface used between any two components like CLI and daemon; the Communicate trait implementations use binary rkyv format with the signal-frame mechanism; signal-frame provides connection setup, asynchronous unique IDs for request-reply correlation, and connection handshake for initialization; every component also needs a universal MAIL HANDLING system - a mail state manager that queues messages between sender and daemon receiver; mail accepted into the queue is as-good-as-fed-in because the queue commits intent to process; the reply confirms processing has occurred; the reply carries a DATABASE MARKER - hash plus counter - so the client can verify which transaction the response corresponds to and guarantee local state consistency; this gives clients a strong local-state guarantee tied to the daemons authoritative database state; the asynchronous unique ID system plus database marker reply together support full async messaging with provable state evolution *remote procedure call*] Medium High Zero [])) (4frx ([(Technology (Software (Observability Tracing)))] Decision [A trace-client library lives in the repo and owns the display plus SEMA-log features. The CLI becomes a thin wrapper that enables and calls the library features rather than reimplementing trace listener and decoder logic per component. Refines Spirit 1489 with concrete shape — trace genericization lands as a workspace library, not just a generated-per-component generic surface. Library location open — candidates include triad-runtime, a dedicated trace-client crate, or a workspace-level signal-trace crate.] Medium High Zero [])) (7yth ([(Technology (Software (Intelligence AgentSystems)))] Decision [Agent is its own triad component: agent CLI + agent-daemon + signal-agent + owner-signal-agent.] Medium High Zero [])) (b2jg ([(Technology (S