tern where macros are reusable building blocks rather than monolithic transformations.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (daht ([(Technology (Software (Distributed EventDrivenArchitecture)))] Principle [Signal is the first gate: invalid or unacceptable messages are rejected at the Signal layer and return to the client without reaching Nexus or SEMA. *message queuing*] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (dcqz ([(Technology (Software (Distributed ProtocolDesign)))] Decision [|The wire-header pattern is extensible: current 8-byte (64-bit) header is the base; longer headers (256-byte / 512-byte / variable) hold most of the message frame structure. The shorter 8-byte header lives INSIDE the longer one as a prefix - always parseable by code expecting only 8 bytes. Vectors of data come AFTER the header as memory arrays; the header carries length + type-of-vector indexes pointing at them. Most of the message structure fits in the schema-defined header positions; the post-header memory holds the bulk payload (variable-length vectors, blob data). Schema declares which fields fit in 8 bytes vs which need the extended header positions. Header growth is by extension not replacement.|] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (ddtj ([(Technology (Software (Quality Testing)))] Constraint [Schema files are NOTA documents: every .schema fixture used in tests must be NOTA-legal and parsable by nota-next before schema-specific lowering. Tests should exercise .schema files as real parseable NOTA artifacts, not non-NOTA sketches.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (dtwe ([(Technology (Software (Programming CodeGeneration)))] Decision [Schema-generated Rust should emit into a dedicated schema module tree inside the crate source, with generated lib-style module files mirroring the schema module layout before the normal Rust build consumes them.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (duis ([(Technology (Software (Distributed ProtocolDesign)))] Decision [|Sema gets its own short header symmetric with signal-side. The sema-engine operations (executor, lowering, command dispatch, database reads/writes) ALL carry the same 8-enum 64-bit short-header structure, with sema-specific root + sub-enum vocabulary. Tap-anywhere observability extends to sema-side operations identically to signal-side. Two parallel headers — signal-header and sema-header — using the same macro machinery but routing to different paths. This is the symmetric counterpart to spirit 388: short headers are universal across both the wire (signal) and the engine (sema) surfaces.|] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (dx10 ([(Technology (Software (Distributed ProtocolDesign)))] Decision [|Agent short identifiers — when an orchestrator launches a new role or unique agent, the agent receives a short ID derived from the first three bytes of its Criome master-identity public key. The short ID is exposed via a shortest_id() method on the full ID; the method checks for collision against currently-active agents and returns the shortest non-colliding prefix (3 bytes by default; can widen up to the NOTA namespace width if collisions force it). Because identities are binary in the signal layer, the collision check is a direct byte comparison on the public-key prefix. *IPC*|] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (e0gd ([(Technology (Software (Programming Parsing)))] Principle [Block reassembly after parsing: blocks concatenate one-after-another. The parser output is composable - blocks join sequentially. Reassembly does not require nesting reconstruction; parsed blocks are first-class units that can be re-emitted in order.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (e2si ([(Technology (Software (Programming Grammars)))] Correction [|Schema root input and output definitions should support inline payload definitions directly in the root vector, for example [Record { Topic * Description * }], rather than forcing operation roots to be separated from payload bodies through namespace retags when the inline form is the beautiful compact shape.|] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (e7pe ([(Technology (Software (Programming Metaprogramming)))] Principle [Schema declaration crystallizes the architecture that was already instinctively emerging in earlier ASCII work, before the component+database practical approach. The practical detour through components-with-databases revealed the substrate need; now schema is the stable formalization of what was being reached for intuitively. Schema serves AS self-describing code documentation AND self-describing wire format simultaneously - one .schema file generates both the code AND the wire shape, AND documents itself. The 'redefines or more like crystallizes' framing: schema is not a NEW architecture, it is the load-bearing precipitation of what the workspace was already structurally moving toward.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (eb5l ([(Technology (Software (Data Modeling)))] Correction [|Schema structure is sectioned — outer vector contains multiple sub-vectors, each being a distinct section/category. First sub-vector is one type of objects (e.g. messaging/operations); second sub-vector is another standard part of a schema definition (e.g. type namespace for new object names). Designer 326 section 2 example was wrong because it was a single flat vector — that misses the section structure.|] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (edqu ([(Technology (Software (Data Serialization)))] Principle [Contract schemas should be explicit content-addressable layout schemas for rkyv migration] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (eeeo ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture))) (Technology (Software (Distributed ProtocolDesign)))] Decision [signal-standard is a new shared schema holding only genuine cross-component standards - the vocabulary every component conforms to, not a grab-bag of conveniences. Its first and central content is the cross-component classification: the ComponentKind roster and the differentiator. It is the second non-component shared signal- library alongside signal-frame, imported by all component contracts with each component's local ComponentKind copy retired. Not signal-system, which is the system component's own contract and would be overloaded, and not signal-frame, whose charter is domain-free frame mechanics. The roster is closed-but-partitioned - a system or core zone plus reserved room to grow, modeled on the signal namespace partition - so adding a component is a local edit, not a workspace-wide rebuild. In the migration, signal-persona's ComponentPrincipal collapses into the imported ComponentKind with no persona-local alias.] Medium Minimum Zero [criome router])) (ejum ([(Technology (Software (Data Formats)))] Clarification [Schema headers are ordered enum-root declarations, not namespace vectors.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (ek8w ([(Information Curation)] Decision [Intent agglomeration and refresh is triggered by an automated auditor that auto-proposes refreshes; the psyche confirms the retire of source records. Automated discovery with human-gated removal, preserving the conservative over-removal-is-worse discipline.] Medium Minimum Zero [auditor spirit agglomeration])) (en7k ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Clarification [Splitting SEMA out of the daemon is only a distant future consideration if the database itself must become larger and more available; it is not the current per-plane-crate design and should not be emphasized in a way that confuses agents.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (eo25 ([(Technology (Software Quality))] Clarification [Pi harness aborts around compaction are a recurring reliability problem, not an isolated one-off; future investigations should treat similar stop-after-compaction symptoms as harness bug candidates unless user/manual abort is confirmed. *debugging*] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (ermr ([(Technology (Software (Security Authentication)))] Decision [|Cross-system trust root for criome: a cluster-root identity signs member keys, and that signature is criome registry admission gate (RegisterIdentity requires a valid root signature); cross-system peer