lized-time windows where routing through the ordinary component fabric would add the wrong latency or ownership. That direct lane carries criome agreement and authorization messages, not arbitrary component payload transport, so criome remains auth/agreement-only while router remains the general transport fabric. Mirror version-controls and moves objects. The tailnet provides confidentiality and criome BLS attestations provide per-frame authenticity. Intra-host sandbox-to-router transport is tap/L3 for now, with vsock deferred because it loses SO_PEERCRED. This realizes router ownership of ordinary remote delivery while making criome's own time-sensitive peer agreement protocol a direct criome lane.] Medium Minimum Zero [router criome mirror spirit])) (lugr ([(Governance Policy)] Principle [When psyche questions are open, agents should infer a lean from psyche patterns and present uncertainty instead of freezing.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (lvs5 ([(Technology (Software (Security Cryptography)))] Correction [|Criome's cryptography is BLS (BLS12-381 curve, BLS signature scheme), not Ed25519. The pre-Criome agent-identity path in /150 §2 incorrectly said 'ephemeral Ed25519 keypair' — that's the workspace's default for SSH but it's a different cryptographic primitive than Criome will use. For migration smoothness, the pre-Criome path should use BLS12-381 keypairs (same primitive as Criome) so an agent's identity transitions cleanly when Criome lands. Alternative shape (full re-sign on Criome adoption) is workable but discards continuity; the BLS-from-day-one approach is cheaper at migration time. Updates /150 §2 + §8 Q4.|] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (lw73 ([(Technology (Software (Distributed ProtocolDesign)))] Decision [Spirit should keep separate ordinary and owner sockets for now; permissions are enforced by filesystem socket access while development still runs locally under trusted user setup. A future general socket with explicit permission prefix is possible but not t