, beingness of the object — e.g. Help, Query, Message); bytes 1-7 are 7 data-carrying sub-variants forming the verb namespace. 8 enums total: 1 root + 7 sub. The verb-space is itself a single enum. Macro standardizes the verb-at-root pattern. Verb chosen as load-bearing root because verbs unify across namespaces *encoding*|] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (u7fj ([(Technology (Software Distributed))] Decision [Signal engine role is message triage only — admission, dispatch, identity-stamping, validation, wire-frame handling. Signal does not own heavy algorithmic logic or decision-making; it routes input to Nexus and routes Nexus replies back to wire output. *remote procedure call*] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (ucqp ([(Technology (Software (Data Modeling)))] Principle [Schema namespaces can import local type namespaces from other schemas] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (ud6l ([(Technology (Software (Engineering VersionControl)))] Decision [Bird/Zeus update authority uses LiGoldragon main by default, not per-user branches] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (ue6x ([(Technology (Software (Data Persistence)))] Principle [Component data lifecycle should prefer explicit archival lowering before hard deletion: stale or low-certainty data is marked and moved out of the hot working database to keep runtime state manageable, while recoverability is best-effort rather than guaranteed unless a stronger retention class says otherwise.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (ue7r ([(Technology (Software (Observability Tracing)))] Constraint [Do not enable tracing on the tracing interface itself for now; trace enablement should be controlled per crate or component so the trace system does not recursively trace its own trace events.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (ugig ([(Technology (Software (Programming TypeSystems)))] Decision [The schema root plane surface is a data-carrying enum named Plane with Signal Nexus and Sema variants; the variants carry the actual plane messages so runtime code can match directly on the plane instead of pairing a thin kind tag with a separate envelope.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (uhz9 ([(Technology (Software (Programming DomainSpecificLanguages)))] Clarification [Schema is the composability and programmability layer on top of NOTA: it turns NOTA into a system for describing composable data types and data-driven behavior, programmable by the user to create new interfaces for specialized engine behavior expressed as a node-graph data type. Schemas nest: an engine may contain sub-engines, each with its own schema and interface, so signal, nexus, and sema are the three top schemas but internal sub-behaviors get their own. The namespace mirrors Rust modules: one file with fully-qualified colon-separated names, or split into files like Rust modules, importable and re-exportable. A schema is a key-value struct at the top whose entries declare the module public symbols. Imports are a key-value map of module name to a data-carrying variant naming the import KIND such as import-all, from-git, from-path, adjacent-directory, same-directory, or from-repository-root, so the import system is modular across scenarios.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (ujb2 ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Design)))] Principle [The current target assumes at most seven root data-carrying variants for a component surface; if a component needs substantially more, that is pressure to split the component or surface.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (upuf ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Management)))] Decision [The system-specialist role is being renamed to system-operator; the report directory and orchestration protocol should use system-operator.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (uqoi ([(Technology (Software (Data Modeling)))] Correction [The header declaration is a vector of ordered enum variants.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (uti9 ([(Technology (Software (Programming Macros)))] Decision [|The schema-schema is implemented as core Rust code - the macro interface. It exposes what other macros build on. The macro interface defines the different inputs and what they are called (a macros input type IS its name in the macro). People build their own macros against this core interface.|] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (ux4w ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Principle [|rkyv's natural storage layout uses a larger namespace than the data strictly needs (a bool occupies a byte; a small-variant enum's discriminator fits within a byte even when there are only 2-3 active variants). This headroom enables a class of zero-cost schema changes that require no data migration whatsoever: adding a fourth unit variant to a three-variant enum that still fits in the byte. Constraint: variant order must be preserved (existing payload bytes must still decode under the new schema). The schema-layout schema must expose this headroom (e.g., declared discriminator width) so the migration-derivation step can identify zero-cost changes and skip the migration step. Other zero-cost-class candidates: adding fields at the end of a struct under append-only encoding; widening fixed-width integer fields where rkyv reserves space.|] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (uylt ([(Technology (Software (Operations BuildSystem)))] Clarification [Schema imports should resolve by crate name from the imported crate's standard schema folder, so schema and source travel together as one compilation and namespace unit.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (uz4p ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture)))] Constraint [|The schema-crystallized architectural principles (the records captured in this turn: schema crystallizes architecture; extensible header pattern; deep tree of enum-struct with type index; two languages internal/external; interact trait and interaction actor mediation; effect table mapping; actor fan-out execution) are LOAD-BEARING for all subsequent architecture and intent work. They must be embedded EVERYWHERE: workspace ESSENCE.md, AGENTS.md hard overrides, skill files, every per-repo INTENT.md, every ARCHITECTURE.md. Existing material that contradicts these principles must be rewritten or significantly changed - not optional, not aspirational; this IS the operating architecture going forward. Applies the meta-principle from record 636 (psyche design decisions apply globally) at the architectural scale.|] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (v5d4 ([(Technology (Software (Operations Deployment)))] Constraint [Passing sandbox testing is a precondition for the lean-stack cutover to main deployment] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (v6xs ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Documentation)))] Constraint [Schema implementation reports must separate real implemented behavior from design-only behavior.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (v91q ([(Technology (Software (Distributed EventDrivenArchitecture)))] Principle [|Actor execution produces FAN-OUT outputs. When an interaction actor decides an outcome, it emits multiple things in parallel: execution effects, responses returned to the originating actors, AND additional messages dispatched to other actors (typical: send a mutation message to the database actor, send a notification message to the subscription actor, return a reply to the requester - all from one interaction-actor decision). Single-input-multiple-output is the normal shape; the actor never produces just one thing. The schema encodes the fan-out outputs declaratively - per interact-trait variant, the set of possible outputs is fixed and closed.|] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (veqq ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Principle [|The update mechanism (sema-upgrade) is a structural prerequisite for any deployed persona component. The deploy → restart → update flow means a daemon coming up against an existing redb must either find no schema drift (no migration needed) or have a migration path through sema-upgrade. Without that path, any contract edit after first deploy breaks the next restart. The implication for getting mind + orchestrate deployed: their schema must be stable enough OR sema-upgrade must cover their migration before deployment, or the operator must be willing to drop-and-rebuild on every contract edit until sema-upgrade catches them.|] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (vhs2 ([(Technology (Software (Engineering Architecture))) (Technology (Software (Security Authentication))) (Technology (Software (Distributed ProtocolDesign)))] Decision [Criome's internal language is a limited typed policy language over public-key identity atoms - NOT a general-purpose virtual machine - drawing its limited-operation discipline from the constrained VMs of Ethereum, Tezos, and Solana. Public keys are the atomic unit of identity; above them it composes complex identity contracts from signature and time-lock mechanics: signature quorums of k-of-n form and thresholds that increase or decrease over elapsed time. It carries explicit divergence-reconciliation objects for when two networks split and how the reconciliation is determined, where conflict resolution may be mediated by an LLM-oracle call to a provider which itself resolves through one of those identity contracts - for example a paid expert panel adjudicating the fairest resolution model. This is criome's Nexus object and verb vocabulary, the objects and operations the identity world treats, to be researched, defined in schema, and prototyped.] Medium Minimum Zero [criome Nexus])) (vpp2 ([(Technology (Software (Security Privacy)))] Decision [Infrastructure-improvement intent is not private by default; privacy classification should separate private personal substance from general infrastructure guidance that benefits all agents.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (vu2k ([(Technology (Software (Data Modeling)))] Clarification [A pure-projection Horizon settled as the runtime shape by the rewrite charter needs the types-only-module schema shape. The report-39 finding is that a 4-position schema document forces a signal plane; a Horizon that is a pure projection library with no runtime triad therefore needs a types-only-module schema variant so the datatypes generate without forcing an Input or Output signal plane onto Horizon. This is the surviving mechanical constraint from the now-closed Horizon-runtime-shape trichotomy.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (vvua ([(Technology (Software (Programming DomainSpecificLanguages)))] Correction [Spirit schema files have no outer root parentheses, declare header/root first, encode enum-like surfaces as ordered variant vectors, defer namespace imports beyond MVP, and cover ordinary signal, owner signal, and Sema headers.] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (w1ss ([(Technology (Software (Data SchemaEvolution)))] Decision [|Persona daemon schema migration uses in-process versioned reads. Every stored record carries a schema-version tag; the daemon dispatches read-side on the tag, migrating older records on read into the current shape (optionally rewriting upgraded). No external migrator binary; zero downtime per schema bump. Trade-offs accepted: the daemon links every prior schema version's types, and read paths fork by version (squashable later through explicit version-collapse work). Applies to every persona triad, not just spirit. Per-record-version (not per-table or per-database) is implied by the selection wording "stores a schema-version tag on every record".|] Medium Minimum Zero [])) (w2g3 ([(Technology (Software (Security Authentication))) (Technology (Software (Security Authorization)))] Decision [Spirit should be an early pilot consumer of Criome-backed operation authorization: Spirit operations that require authentication ask Criome to authorize an exact content-addressed request or log-message digest, with the concrete envelope design still open.] Medium Minimum Zero [spirit criome])) (w9gq ([(Technology (Software (Programming Macros)))] Decision [|Every schema file is loaded with a default schema attached implicitly - the schema-schema. The schema-schema defines the structural shape expected for schema files (root struct + sections). It is